        output='Based on the provided sections of the S-1 prospectus, here are the details regarding the directed share program, lock-up agreements, shares eligible for resale, and restrictions on transfer:\n\n### 1. Directed Share Program\n*   **Reservation of Shares:** At the company\'s request, the underwriters reserved a specified percentage of the Class A common stock offered in the IPO for sale at the IPO price to employees, designated individuals, business partners, and friends/family of management.\n*   **No Lock-Up Restriction:** Shares purchased by these individuals through the directed share program are **not** subject to lock-up restrictions.\n*   **Impact on Public Float:** The number of shares available to the general public will be reduced by the amount sold to these individuals. Any reserved shares that go unpurchased will be offered to the general public on the same basis as the other shares.\n*   **Administration & Indemnification:** Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC and its affiliates will administer the global program. The company agreed to indemnify the underwriters against certain liabilities (including those under the Securities Act) related to the sale of these reserved shares.\n*   **Ownership Table Exclusion:** The beneficial ownership table in the prospectus does not reflect any shares that may be purchased through this program.\n\n### 2. Lock-Up Agreements\n*   **Founder & Significant Investors (366 Days):** Elon Musk and certain significant investors are subject to a 366-day lock-up period covering an aggregate number of shares (including 100% of the shares owned by Musk). \n    *   These specific shares are **not** subject to any early release provisions.\n    *   They cannot sell, pledge, lend, hedge, or transfer these shares without the prior written consent of Goldman Sachs & Co. LLC, except in specific scenarios like mergers or acquisitions.\n*   **Standard Lock-Up (180 Days):** The company, its directors, executive officers, and other remaining shareholders are subject to a 180-day lock-up period restricting the sale, short sale, transfer, hedging, or pledging of their equity interests.\n*   **Early Release Provisions:** There are automatic early release triggers for a portion of the 180-day and 366-day locked-up securities. These releases can occur based on specific events, such as the public release of the company\'s quarterly financial results.\n\n### 3. Shares Eligible for Resale\n*   **IPO Shares:** All shares of Class A common stock sold in the IPO will be freely tradable without restriction or further registration under the Securities Act, unless held by "affiliates" (as defined by Rule 144).\n*   **Restricted Securities (Pre-IPO):** All Class A and Class B shares issued prior to the IPO closing (including those held by Musk and existing investors) are deemed "restricted securities." They can only be sold publicly if registered or if they qualify for an exemption under Rule 144 or Rule 701.\n*   **Post-Lock-Up & Rule 144:** Once the lock-up agreements expire, a substantial number of Class A shares (including those converted from Class B on a one-for-one basis) will become eligible for sale under Rule 144. Some shares may be available for resale under Rule 144 starting 90 days post-offering, subject to lock-up terms.\n*   **Registration Rights:** Holders of a specific aggregate of Class A shares possess registration rights via an Investors\' Rights Agreement. If the company registers these shares, they become immediately eligible for public sale without Securities Act restrictions (subject to affiliate limitations).\n*   **Market Impact Warning:** The prospectus warns that the sale (or the perception of future sales) of substantial amounts of stock by Musk or existing shareholders could negatively impact the market price and the company\'s ability to raise equity capital.\n\n### 4. Restrictions on Transfer\n*   **Class B Common Stock Auto-Conversion:** Each share of Class B common stock carries 10 votes. However, if a Class B share is transferred to another party (other than a "Permitted Transfer" as defined in the corporate charter), it is **automatically cancelled and converted** into one share of Class A common stock (which carries only 1 vote).\n*   **Preferred Stock Auto-Conversion:** Similarly, if a share of Series A or Series B Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is transferred outside of a Permitted Transfer, it is automatically cancelled and converted into a corresponding alternative series share (e.g., Series A-1).\n*   **Hedging and Derivatives Ban:** The lock-up agreements explicitly prohibit shareholders from entering into swaps, short sales, or other agreements that transfer the economic consequences of ownership, effectively closing loopholes that would allow insiders to cash out or hedge their positions during the lock-up period.\n*   **Affiliate Limitations:** Shareholders deemed "affiliates" of the company face ongoing regulatory restrictions and volume limitations on how and when they can transfer or sell their shares in the public market under SEC Rule 144.',
